This paper deals with the computational complexity of finding Nash equilibria in games, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves the concept of fixed points in linear systems, which is related to computational complexity (cs.CC). The use of trees and acyclic graphs suggests a connection to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also involves the use of approximation algorithms, which is a topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
